	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>tokumaru</b> [ Sat Jul 26, 2014 8:54 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: How do i check all 8 individual bits within a register?</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Not equal to what, exactly? Here's all I can say without understanding exactly what you want to do:<br /><br />To check individual bits you usually AND the value with a mask that has the specific bit you want to test set. For example, if you want to test the state of bit 2, you'd use AND #%00000100. If the result is 0, the bit is clear, otherwise the bit is set.<br /><br />Another way to look at bits is to shift them into the carry flag (using ASL, LSR, ROL or ROR), so you can use BCC or BCS to test them. This might be the better option if you want to check all bits in a byte.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


